INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '034b0bb1-c9b8-45b9-aea1-9e467b8c7741',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$C Undefined Behavior — Don't Trigger It$escape$,
  $escape$Undefined behavior is a fundamental concept in C programming. It occurs when a program performs an operation that the C Standard does not specify the result for. This can happen due to incorrect usage of pointers, array indices, or other language features. In C, examples of undefined behavior include dereferencing a null pointer, accessing an array out of bounds, and performing arithmetic on a pointer that is not properly aligned. The C Standard does not guarantee the results of such operations, making it difficult to debug and predict program behavior.

To avoid undefined behavior, it's essential to understand the C Standard's guidelines and use language features correctly. For instance, always check for null pointer dereferences using the `==` operator, and use `size_t` to ensure array indices are within bounds.

```c
if (ptr != NULL) {
    // safe dereference
}
```$escape$,
  $escape$if (ptr != NULL) {
    // safe dereference
}$escape$,
  $escape$c$escape$,
